# Security Rules — Non-Negotiable

## Never log sensitive values

```go
// WRONG — logs the raw token; anyone with log access has the token
log.InfoCtx(ctx, "token validated", "token", rawToken)
log.InfoCtx(ctx, "user auth", "password_hash", hash)

// RIGHT — log only the prefix (first 8 chars, safe to display)
log.InfoCtx(ctx, "token validated", "token_prefix", token[:8]+"...")
```

Forbidden values in log output: raw tokens, password hashes, Argon2id hashes, email addresses, IP addresses, PII fields, `content` from memories.

## Return PERMISSION_DENIED (not NOT_FOUND) for cross-tenant resource access

This prevents timing and enumeration attacks. An attacker should not be able to determine whether a resource (agent, token, memory) exists in another org by observing the HTTP status code or response time.

```go
// If an agent exists in org B and an org A request asks for it:
// WRONG — tells the attacker the agent exists
return status.Errorf(codes.NotFound, "agent not found in your org")

// RIGHT — ambiguous; attacker cannot distinguish exists-in-other-org from doesn't-exist
return status.Errorf(codes.PermissionDenied,
    "agent is not authorized for this organization")
```

## Every DB write has org_id in both INSERT and the constraint check

```sql
-- WRONG — no org_id check; malformed request could insert wrong org data
INSERT INTO ibex_core.agents (id, name) VALUES ($1, $2);

-- RIGHT
INSERT INTO ibex_core.agents (id, org_id, name, slug)
VALUES ($1, $2, $3, $4)
-- RLS will also reject if app.current_org_id doesn't match $2
```

## All external input is validated before use

```go
// WRONG — using header value directly
agentID := r.Header.Get("X-IBEX-Agent-ID")
// agentID could be "'; DROP TABLE agents;--"

// RIGHT — parse and validate before use
agentIDStr := r.Header.Get("X-IBEX-Agent-ID")
agentID, err := uuid.Parse(agentIDStr)
if err != nil {
    return writeError(w, http.StatusBadRequest, apierror.ErrCodeMissingAgentID, "Invalid X-IBEX-Agent-ID header")
}
// Now agentID is a UUID type; injection is impossible
```

## No hardcoded credentials anywhere in the codebase

Run `git grep -r "password\|secret\|token\|api_key" --include="*.go" --include="*.py" --include="*.ts"` before every PR. CI runs `trufflehog` on every commit.

## Permission check before every state mutation

```go
// WRONG — assumes the caller has permission because they called the function
func (s *AgentService) Delete(ctx context.Context, agentID uuid.UUID) error {
    return s.store.Delete(ctx, agentID)
}

// RIGHT — explicit permission check before mutation
func (s *AgentService) Delete(ctx context.Context, orgID, agentID uuid.UUID, callerPerms permissions.Bitmap) error {
    if !callerPerms.Has(permissions.AgentDelete) {
        return apierror.ErrForbidden
    }
    return s.store.Delete(ctx, orgID, agentID) // orgID from verified token, not request body
}
```

## Rate limit all public endpoints

No endpoint exposed to the internet is without rate limiting. Auth endpoints are additionally limited per-IP. Token creation is limited to 10/minute per org.

## HTTPS everywhere — no plaintext in production

All inter-service communication uses mTLS in production. The dev compose stack uses plaintext on `ibex_internal` network only. No insecure transport in CI against staging.
